he shot-callers of space. They do not want to read a half-baked joke that =
=E2=80=9Cactually, this is rocket science.=E2=80=9D They=E2=80=99ve heard i=
t before. It doesn=E2=80=99t fly.
But today, dear readers, Payload is temporarily parting with our time-worn =
tradition in this prospectus summary and we=E2=80=99re going to let the cli=
ch=C3=A9s rip.=C2=A0
A new space age is upon us, characterized by fierce competition between sup=
erpowers and startups alike. Dozens of space unicorns are hitting escape ve=
locity. Finally, unlike crypto, we actually are going to the Moon. Very soo=
n.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re living through an age of historic firsts and massive developm=
ents, good and bad, that are happening daily in space. Just in the last few=
 weeks, we=E2=80=99ve tracked the following in our daily newsletter:=C2=A0
On July 30, a massive Chinese Long March rocket made an uncontrolled reentr=
y (aka tumbled back from orbit to Earth), with debris falling on Malaysia a=
nd Indonesia.=C2=A0
On Aug. 4, five separate launchers flew orbital missions in one day. Four o=
f the launches were conducted by American companies, one was China=E2=80=99=
s state-owned aerospace corporation.=C2=A0
That same day, Blue Origin launched six people to suborbital space, includi=
ng YouTuber and Dude Perfect cofounder Coby Cotton (his ticket was crowdfun=
ded by a DAO).=C2=A0=C2=A0
SpaceX is launching its Falcon 9 at a less than weekly rate in 2022 and has=
 refurbished and reflown some of the first-stage boosters in under a month.=
 The company also just conducted its first static fire test of the gargantu=
an Super Heavy booster at its Starbase in south Texas.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Three separate launch unicorns=E2=80=93ABL Space Systems, Firefly, and Rela=
tivity=E2=80=93are poised to attempt to reach orbit for the first time in t=
he coming weeks and months.=C2=A0
A wave of multibillion-dollar mergers is sweeping over the legacy satellite=
 sector, with details emerging about two blockbuster deals that are likely =
to move forward.=C2=A0
All the while, the James Webb Space Telescope has been sending back unreal =
photos of our galaxy and literally letting us travel back billions of years=
 in time.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s plenty more where that came from. In this essay, we=E2=80=
=99ll tell you everything you need to know about how we got here and where =
we=E2=80=99re headed.
Payload was founded on the premise that the space industry is at an inflect=
ion point. What was once monopolized by superpowers is now being privatized=
, with companies taking greater share of low-Earth orbit, rocket launches, =
and more. So, because we passionately believe in this inflection point thes=
is, we=E2=80=99ve packaged this new space primer as an S-1. It=E2=80=99s an=
 intellectual exercise unpacking what taking the space industry, broadly sp=
eaking, public. Is it tech-growth stage? Yes. Is it profitable? Ehhhhh. Wha=
t else do you need to know? Well, let=E2=80=99s dive in=E2=80=A6
MARKET, INDUSTRY AND OTHER DATA
Space: A brief history=C2=A0
On Oct. 4, 1957, the Soviets launched the first artificial satellite into s=
pace. The soccer ball-sized spacecraft was named Sputnik. That word, we thi=
nk, went to become one of the most famous Russian words in non-Russian tong=
ues and English-language history books. The =E2=80=9CSputnik crisis=E2=80=
=9D caught the West completely by surprise, clearly dividing history and th=
e Cold War into two separate eras: =E2=80=9Cpre-Sputnik=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=
=9Cpost-Sputnik.=E2=80=9D
Perceptions are everything. The New York Times had a rare three-fold headli=
ner story on the Soviets=E2=80=99 successful launch. Paranoia set in among =
American policymakers and the general public awakened to the space age. Pos=
t-Sputnik, the perception of a Pax Americana and pacing Soviet Union gave w=
ay to a public view that the Soviets had achieved a step change not just in=
 space. The Soviets were running up a =E2=80=9Ctechnology gap=E2=80=9D over=
 the Americans.=C2=A0
The race was on, with the two superpowers=E2=80=99 space programs kicking o=
ff a new front in the Cold War and one of the greatest technological showdo=
wns of modern history.=C2=A0
Less than one month after Sputnik 1, the Soviets sent a ~1,120 lb. satellit=
e into Earth orbit with radio transmitters, a thermal control unit, sealed =
cabin, and a husky-spitz mut named Laika. The Soviets hadn=E2=80=99t build =
any Earth return capabilities into Sputnik 2, so sadly, Laika didn=E2=80=99=
t make it =F0=9F=98=93.
The pressure was on the Eisenhower administration: do something! The US del=
ivered with Explorer 1, the Americans=E2=80=99 first satellite, successfull=
y launched into space on Jan. 31, 1958, a full 119 days after the Soviets. =
Explorer 1 was the size of a beach ball (note: Payload only uses Earth spor=
ts balls as a metric unit for spacecraft management).=C2=A0
Still, congressional leaders felt that space deserved more of a federal foc=
us=E2=80=93and Eisenhower established NASA in 1958 and abolished NACA (the =
agency=E2=80=99s predecessor, started in 1915). NASA=E2=80=99s charter was =
to exercise =E2=80=9Ccontrol over aeronautical and space activities sponsor=
ed by the United States.=E2=80=9D NASA was to handle civilian space efforts=
, but the Pentagon still had authority over military space programs.=C2=A0
Over the next three years, the Soviets and Americans worked on their space =
programs, but on April 12, 1961, it was the Soviets who sent the first pers=
on to space: Russian Lt. Yuri Gagarin. Mercury-era astronaut Alan Shepard b=
ecame the first American to reach space (sub-orbitally) less than a month l=
ater, on May 5, 1961.=C2=A0
That same year, JFK set forth a national goal: =E2=80=9CLanding a man on th=
e moon and returning him safely to Earth within a decade.=E2=80=9D The Amer=
icans, it should come as no surprise, were able to meet this ambitious call=
 less than a decade later, with Neil Armstrong taking =E2=80=9Cone small st=
ep=E2=80=9D but a =E2=80=9Cgiant leap for mankind=E2=80=9D on July 20, 1969=
 (nice).=C2=A0
As Tom Wolfe expertly chronicled in The Right Stuff, Air Force test pilots =
who were flying planes with rockets strapped on them in the desert would be=
come the US=E2=80=99s first astronauts (part of the Mercury program). The A=
pollo era, though, was a high watermark for the US space program, no matter=
 how you slice it. Astronauts were living legends and international celebri=
ties. They drove (or, more accurately, raced) Corvettes across town in Hous=
ton. Life magazine struck a deal with the astronauts and their families to =
tell their stories (albeit carefully overseen by NASA handlers).=C2=A0
After the historic Apollo 11, the US would go on to send an additional five=
 manned missions =E2=80=93Apollos 12, 14, 15, 16, and 17=E2=80=93 and 11 me=
n to the moon and back. Since December 19, 1972, no humans have been back t=
o the lunar surface.=C2=A0
Winning the race to the Moon and inventing countless technologies out of th=
in air=E2=80=93all while using less processing power for the whole mission =
than an iPhone uses today=E2=80=93came at astronomical expense. Going to th=
e Moon cost $283B, according to one tally. In relative terms, NASA's budget=
 peaked from 1964 to 1966, when it consumed ~4% of all US federal governmen=
t spend. That number now sits an order of magnitude lower at 0.4%.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s not to say that space activity dropped in the =E2=80=9870s. =
Companies began to launch [ https://substack.com/redirect/203ff82d-7f7c-41c=
e-bb1a-b654a2087356?r=3D9p0gt ] communications satellites to carry voice, d=
ata, and eventually, TV. In 1973, the Pentagon kicked off the Global Positi=
oning System (GPS) project. The project would take two decades to complete,=
 with a prototype GPS bird going up 22,000+ miles above Earth in 1978 and t=
he full constellation coming online in the mid =E2=80=9890s.=C2=A0
All the while, interstellar robotic probes pushed further out into the cosm=
os. In 1971, an American spacecraft became the first to orbit another plane=
t (Mars). The next year, the Soviets made history by landing a spacecraft o=
n Mars (the soft landing wasn=E2=80=99t so soft, as video transmission ceas=
ed from the craft after 20 seconds). They later landed not-so-softly on Ven=
us, too. By the end of the 1970s, the US=E2=80=99s Voyager 1 and 2 spacecra=
ft had sent back stunning photos of Jupiter and Saturn. The Voyagers journe=
yed to Neptune and Uranus (no really).=C2=A0
SPACE STATION
The Soviets launched the world=E2=80=99s first space station=E2=80=93Salyut=
 1=E2=80=93into low-Earth orbit (LEO) in 1971. The Soyuz 11 crew stayed abo=
ard Salyut 1, but were killed by asphyxia due to valve failure right before=
 reentering Earth=E2=80=99s atmosphere. The Salyut program would see a tota=
l of six stations launched=E2=80=93four for scientific research and two for=
 military reconnaissance.=C2=A0
The US launched its first space station=E2=80=93Skylab=E2=80=93between 1973=
 and 1974. Three crews occupied Skylab for ~24 weeks, and though the microg=
ravity lab and Earth-observing workshop was meant to last nine years, it qu=
ickly lost altitude and ultimately ended as a failure. Skylab reentered Ear=
th=E2=80=99s atmosphere, and as it disintegrated, cast debris across rural =
regions of western Australia and into the Indian Ocean. At least nobody die=
d?
Skylab and Salyut walked so that the International Space Station (ISS) coul=
d run.=C2=A0
Jointly operated by the US, Russia, Europe, Canada, and Japan, the ISS is o=
ne of the top engineering feats of the modern age. It=E2=80=99s been contin=
uously occupied since 1998, longer than tens of thousands of you reading th=
is have been alive. Right now, as you=E2=80=99re reading this, there are se=
ven people on the ISS: three Russian cosmonauts, three NASA astronauts, and=
 one European Space Agency astronaut.=C2=A0
The ISS is also one of the most expensive things humans have ever built, at=
 a cost of $150 billion (the $50 billion shuttle program is typically inclu=
ded in the cost of the ISS as it is here). The US footed most of the bill, =
and NASA shells out ~$3.1 billion a year to keep things running. All good t=
hings must come to an end, and the ISS is showing its age. The station is e=
xpected to be decommissioned and deorbited into a spacecraft graveyard in t=
he South Pacific Ocean Uninhabited Area at the end of this decade.=C2=A0
SPACE SHUTTLE=C2=A0
Reusability is all the rage in rocket jock circles these days, but the conc=
ept is not new.=C2=A0
You may very well have grown up watching Space Shuttle flights. The iconic =
vehicle was envisioned as a revolutionary transportation system that would =
usher in reliable, =E2=80=9Ccheap=E2=80=9D (or cost-effective) transit to a=
nd from LEO. The spacecraft was reusable (though the boosters that launched=
 it were not). Reusability was a key selling point.=C2=A0
The shuttle became the American space program=E2=80=99s workhorse, and acro=
ss three decades, the fleet of Columbia, Challenger, Discovery, Atlantis, a=
nd Endeavour flew 135 missions and 355 humans to space.
But the Shuttle never lived up to its dreams, and by one estimate, cost ~$1=
B per head to transport astronauts to the International Space Station and b=
ack. Tragically, two crews and 14 lives were also lost on the Shuttle.=C2=
=A0
The Obama administration pulled the plug on the government-run program and =
the Shuttle flew its final flight in June 2011. Despite the program=E2=80=
=99s budget overruns and abject dangers, the Shuttle=E2=80=99s final missio=
n was an emotional moment for the nation, NASA=E2=80=99s rank-and-file, spa=
ce buffs, and astronauts alike.=C2=A0
After that, Washington paid Roscosmos, Russia=E2=80=99s space agency, to ta=
ke its crews to the space station aboard Soyuz rockets.=C2=A0
